# Publish and IIS Deploy Conventions

## Publish Profiles (.pubxml)

Two standard profiles, always named consistently:

- `WebApp-FileSystem.pubxml` — ASP.NET Core web apps (IIS-hosted)
- `WinApp-FileSystem.pubxml` — background services / console apps

Always set BOTH `PublishUrl` and `PublishDir` to the same UNC path (Visual Studio uses one, CLI uses the other).

## Publish Destination Paths

Target: `\\<server>\DedgeCommon\Software\DedgeWinApps\<AppName>`

- **Single-project solutions**: folder = solution name (e.g. `\MyApp`)
- **Multi-project solutions**: folder = `<Solution>-<Component>` (e.g. `\MyApp-WebApi`, `\MyApp-ImportService`)

Each component gets its own isolated folder — no shared parent, no DLL collisions.

## Build Script Pattern

Each app should have a `Build-And-Publish.ps1` at the repo root:

```powershell
dotnet publish $projectPath -c Release -p:PublishProfile=WebApp-FileSystem -v minimal
```

The profile handles configuration, runtime, output path, and self-contained mode.

## IIS Deploy Templates

Location: `IIS-DeployApp\templates\<SiteName>_<InstallSource>.deploy.json`

Critical path alignment rule:
- `InstallAppName` must match the folder name on the staging share
- `PhysicalPath` must resolve to the same folder after install
- For multi-project: `InstallAppName` includes component suffix (e.g. `MyApp-WebApi`), but `SiteName`/`VirtualPath` use solution name only

## After Changing IIS-DeployApp Files

Always run `.\IIS-DeployApp\_deploy.ps1` to sync updated scripts/templates to servers.

## Do NOT Use

- **Web Deploy (MSDeploy) profiles** — not used; always use FileSystem method
- **Remote execution via WinRM/Invoke-Command** — blocked on servers; use file-based deploy
